{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"a55164ba39d9cc04cde6ecc2e78fedfe80d239a2b6dd5022ce8919461d7f4d05","slug":"pages.m16-conclusion-of-case-c-q","location":"/pages/253-m16-conclusion-of-case-c-q.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Conclusion of Case C→Q","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"thumbnail":"/textbook/build/c-q_table-f97c9a00310f3588bb14a5186196d34b.png","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"253-m16-conclusion-of-case-c-q.md","url":"/textbook/build/253-m16-conclusion-o-8ad6a99b08c1a5c4243efe3a4f9a9d7b.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We are now done with case C→Q. We learned that this case is further classified into sub-cases, depending on the number of groups that we are comparing (i.e., the number of categories that the explanatory variable has), and the design of the study (independent vs. dependent samples). For each of the three sub-cases that we covered, we learned the appropriate inferential method, and emphasized the idea behind the method, the conditions under which it can be safely used, how to carry it out using software, and the interpretation of the results.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"hnWjPvVO4X"}],"key":"NY3k6KZwHM"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":